            <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/opinion/columns">COLUMNS</a></span></div>

                <h1>Charlotte Simmons takes on the union</h1>
                
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/monday-monday">Monday Monday</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">December 7, 2009 | 5:00am EST</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/12/charlotte-simmons-takes-union" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/12/charlotte-simmons-takes-union&amp;text=Charlotte Simmons takes on the union" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Charlotte%20Simmons%20takes%20on%20the%20union%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2009%2F12%2Fcharlotte-simmons-takes-union" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>The epic battle you&rsquo;ve all been waiting for.</p>
<p>Oh, you want to know who I am first? Three options: 1) read on, it&rsquo;s at the bottom; 2) stop right here, skip to the bottom (preferred choice for people who just want to know my name so they know who to throw eggs at this afternoon); c) the first letter of each of the first 10 paragraphs of last Monday&rsquo;s column spells out my name. No joke. Cleverest thing I&rsquo;ve done this semester.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>I was planning on encapsulating all the things I&rsquo;ve learned from being Monday, Monday (notably, IFC brothers are surprisingly the most sensitive people on campus&shy;&mdash;sorry, guys), but I couldn&rsquo;t pass up the opportunity to do what I set out to do this semester: point out when things are ridiculous and not being acknowledged as such.</p>
<p>Let&rsquo;s be real here, whether or not you liked me this semester, you&rsquo;ve gotten used to the routine. There&rsquo;s nothing like rolling out of bed, picking up your Monday paper, flipping to the opinion section and sprinting over to the nearest wall to pound your head through it. You&rsquo;ll miss me when I&rsquo;m gone. And don&rsquo;t worry, I&rsquo;ll miss you too.</p>
<p>So let&rsquo;s get down to it&mdash;Charlotte Simmons&rsquo;s last-ditch effort to fracture the campus and suck humor out of everyone&rsquo;s life.</p>
<p>Unions. Let&rsquo;s talk.</p>
<p>We have lots of unions on campus. We&rsquo;ve got the West Campus Union, which houses&hellip; like, three armchairs and the DukeCard office (Chick-Fil-A and Alpine don&rsquo;t really count, and I&rsquo;m getting to the Great Hall). We&rsquo;ve got the East Campus Union, which people don&rsquo;t realize is technically different from the Marketplace, primarily because it&rsquo;s not technically different from the Marketplace.</p>
<p>We&rsquo;ve got the Duke University Union. We&rsquo;ve also got the Duke University Confederacy. For those of you who don&rsquo;t know, that&rsquo;s those jag-offs who were ambling around campus shouting &ldquo;Eruditio!&rdquo; and directing air traffic with their stupid arms last Friday. If there&rsquo;s anybody whom you had to pick to be closet to Confederate apologists, wouldn&rsquo;t it be the Old Trinity Club?</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Okay, enough jokes. We&rsquo;ve got Local 77, the Durham union representing Dining Services employees as well as groundskeepers, housekeepers and sanitation workers.</p>
<p>There are a lot of jokes about Local 77, whether you&rsquo;ve known the name of the union or not. We&rsquo;ve all had a situation where we were less than pleased with our food service, ranging from the person behind the counter being too distracted with his cell phone to give you food all the way to the person behind the counter leaping over the counter to beat you up and spit in your ear.</p>
<p>Don&rsquo;t get me wrong, unions are important. Service industry work is no cushy job, and absent organized labor, management runs roughshod over people. Still, although union laborers can be both efficient and friendly, and most of them are, when union contracts means the decision to forgo human decency goes unpunished, we sometimes see a few bad apples allowed to flourish.</p>
<p>A lot of the time, when we&rsquo;re reminded that our bad experiences with Duke Dining might be related to unionized labor, there are problems of short-circuiting in our 80 percent liberal campus brains: U-U-UNIONS ARE SOLVING THE PLIGHT OF THE WORKER, BUT, BUT IMPREGNABLE JOB SECURITY AND PAY SCALE RELATED TO SENIORITY AND NOT PERFORMANCE DOESN&rsquo;T D-D-DISINCENTIVIZE GOOD WORK. (Then your brain explodes, right before your Arabic midterm, no less.)</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=c4087a59c7" method="post">
