            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>But let&rsquo;s avoid the abstract arguments. I didn&rsquo;t do very well in Econ 51, I don&rsquo;t read the newspaper enough to have anecdotes about the auto industry and I&rsquo;m therefore ill-equipped to engage the... you know&hellip; legitimate points about unionized labor versus whatever it is one would call labor that&rsquo;s not in a union.</p>
<p>Regardless of where you fall on the question of unions, it&rsquo;s likely that you don&rsquo;t want to be forced to eat at any one place. It just becomes especially true when it&rsquo;s a place you already don&rsquo;t like. The reason, in fact, that I&rsquo;m talking about unions at all is because Duke Dining Services is thinking about &ldquo;directing&rdquo; student choices when it comes to dining to help make up for a $2 million deficit. If students are required to spend a certain amount at the places with the highest costs (spoiler alert: that&rsquo;s usually the union-contract places), then it won&rsquo;t lose money.</p>
<p>Summary: &ldquo;Directed choice&rdquo; is requiring that you use a certain amount of food points at some of the worst places on campus. Analogy: A robber directs you to empty out the cash register, and gives you full freedom to do what you wish with the money in your wallet.</p>
<p>Where have I heard this before? Oh yes, in &ldquo;Atlas Shrugged,&rdquo; where goddess of being a capitalist drama queen Ayn Rand created a pantheon of characters who solved their bumbling mistakes by forcing other people to pay for them.</p>
<p>Don&rsquo;t worry, though, there&rsquo;s a lot of student input coming in about this plan, and the student voice is being and will be heard. I got a transcript of the most recent meeting between the Duke University Student Dining Advisory Committee and dining officials.</p>
<p>DUSDAC: Hey, this plan is terrible. If we&rsquo;re losing money, why don&rsquo;t we find more creative ways to lower costs?</p>
<p>DINING OFFICIAL (in sign language): I&rsquo;m so sorry, I&rsquo;m pretending to be deaf right now. Can&rsquo;t hear a word you&rsquo;re saying. Get out of my office.</p>
<p>Care about this. I&rsquo;ll be gone next year, meaning I&rsquo;ll have the choice not to eat at bad restaurants. You will be here.</p>

